	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />It's unsensible to me partially because I don't own or use NES hardware yet enjoy playing U/C games, also because they could have implemented whatever logic is behind the CIC reliance another way more uniform to their other boards. My guess is that the reset line is used to define an initial state.
<br />
<br />I didn't mean to imply that it's unsensible regarding security, I don't think it has anything to do with security. NWC carts at the time were certainly kept under tight watch and it's not like your average NWC theif would be a FC gamer.
<br />
<br />BTW, like the NES, SNES (and SFC) and require a CIC to even come out of reset. N64 on the other hand I don't think implements a reset-like mechanism, I think there are two levels of SW protection, one common to all CIC, and the eight or so bootcodes games are developed for.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
