		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">kyuusaku wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">It's unsensible to me partially because I don't own or use NES hardware yet enjoy playing U/C games, also because they could have implemented whatever logic is behind the CIC reliance another way more uniform to their other boards. My guess is that the reset line is used to define an initial state.<br /></div>
<br />
<br />It was used to reset the hardware on the cart.  Sure, you could do it with another reset generator of some form, but that would cost money. Using the lockout chip's already existing reset function saved them money and parts and all that.... and that is the mark of a good engineer.  Being able to extract as much functionality out of the fewest parts is a fun little challenge and the name of the game. <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":-)" title="Smile" />

		

